about.summary: A set of distributions  which can be used  for modelling the response variables in Generalized Additive Models for Location Scale and Shape, Rigby and Stasinopoulos (2005), <doi:10.1111/j.1467-9876.2005.00510.x>. The distributions can be continuous, discrete or mixed  distributions.  Extra distributions can be created, by transforming, any continuous distribution defined on the real line,  to  a distribution defined on ranges 0 to infinity  or  0 to 1,  by using a ''log'' or a ''logit' transformation respectively.

name: r-gamlss.dist
raw_meta_yaml:
{% set version = "5.1-6" %}
{% set posix = 'm2-' if win else '' %}
{% set native = 'm2w64-' if win else '' %}

package:
  name: r-gamlss.dist
  version: {{ version|replace("-", "_") }}

source:
  url:
    - {{ cran_mirror }}/src/contrib/gamlss.dist_{{ version }}.tar.gz
    - {{ cran_mirror }}/src/contrib/Archive/gamlss.dist/gamlss.dist_{{ version }}.tar.gz
  sha256: 3ff0e36dfd7ddea109410c539375a408af8f8f865dd8865555e41fb0402720dd

build:
  merge_build_host: True  # [win]
  number: 1
  rpaths:
    - lib/R/lib/
    - lib/

requirements:
  build:
    - {{ compiler('c') }}              # [not win]
    - {{ compiler('m2w64_c') }}        # [win]
    - {{ posix }}filesystem        # [win]
    - {{ posix }}make
    - {{ posix }}sed               # [win]
    - {{ posix }}coreutils         # [win]
    - {{ posix }}zip               # [win]
  host:
    - r-base
    - r-mass
  run:
    - r-base
    - {{ native }}gcc-libs         # [win]
    - r-mass

test:
  commands:
    - $R -e "library('gamlss.dist')"           # [not win]
    - "\"%R%\" -e \"library('gamlss.dist')\""  # [win]

about:
  home: http://www.gamlss.org/
  license: GPL-2 | GPL-3
  summary: 'A set of distributions  which can be used  for modelling the response variables in
    Generalized Additive Models for Location Scale and Shape, Rigby and Stasinopoulos
    (2005), <doi:10.1111/j.1467-9876.2005.00510.x>. The distributions can be continuous,
    discrete or mixed  distributions.  Extra distributions can be created, by transforming,
    any continuous distribution defined on the real line,  to  a distribution defined
    on ranges 0 to infinity  or  0 to 1,  by using a ''''log'''' or a ''''logit'' transformation
    respectively. '
  license_family: GPL3
  license_file: '{{ environ["PREFIX"] }}/lib/R/share/licenses/GPL-2'

extra:
  recipe-maintainers:
    - conda-forge/r
